data.title: Nintendo reports results for the nine-month period; updates FY guidance
data.description:
• Nintendo press release (OTCPK:NTDOY): for the nine-month period profit of ¥237 billion ($1.5 billion), down 42% from the same period the previous year.
  • Revenue of ¥956B dropped 31%.
  • Sales of Nintendo machines for the nine-month period fell to 9.54 million units from 13.7 million last year.
  • Outlook: Nintendo now expects to sell 11 million Switch consoles for the full fiscal year, lower than its initial projection of 12.5 million.
  • The company now expects to rake in a ¥270-billion ($1.7 billion) profit for the fiscal year through March, down from the previous forecast for ¥300-billion ($1.9 billion).

data.title: UBS proposes a $0.90 per share dividend in 2024; announces continuation of share repurchases
data.description:
• The board of directors proposes a $0.90 per share dividend to UBS Group AG (NYSE:UBS), an increase of 29% Y/Y dividend of $0.70 dividend declared last year.
  • The dividend will be paid on April 17; for shareholders of record April 16; ex-div April 16, subject to approval at the Annual General Meeting, which is scheduled for April 10.
  • The company said that it remains committed to progressive dividends and are accruing for an increase of around 10% in the ordinary dividend per share for the 2025 financial year.
  • "The company completed its planned share repurchases of USD 1bn in Q4 2024, with plans to repurchase up to USD 2bn in the second half of 2025. They aim to exceed full year 2022 levels in 2026, ensuring they maintain their CET1 capital ratio target of ~14%, achieve financial targets, and avoid material changes to Switzerland's capital regime."

data.title: Biggest stock movers Tuesday: PLTR, SYNA, and more
data.description:
Stock futures were cautious in premarket trading on Tuesday following China's imposition of retaliatory tariffs on U.S. imports, responding to U.S. duties on exports from Beijing. This development occurred as President Donald Trump delayed tariffs on Canada and Mexico by a month after last-minute negotiations with Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and Mexican President Claudia Sheinbaum.

Here are some of Tuesday's biggest stock movers:

Biggest stock gainers

  • Palantir Technologies (NASDAQ:PLTR) shares surged 22% following its Q4 results, which exceeded expectations with a 36% Y/Y revenue increase, driven by a 64% rise in U.S. commercial revenue and a 45% increase in U.S. government revenue. For Q1, the company projects revenue between $858M and $862M, surpassing the consensus of $810.81M, and adjusted income from operations between $354M and $358M. For FY2025, Palantir anticipates revenue between $3.741B and $3.757B, exceeding the consensus of $3.54B, with U.S. commercial revenue expected to exceed $1.079B, representing at least 54% growth. Adjusted income from operations is projected between $1.551B and $1.567B, and adjusted free cash flow between $1.5B and $1.7B.

Biggest stock losers

  • Synaptics (NASDAQ:SYNA) shares declined 6% following the announcement that Michael Hurlston is stepping down as President and CEO, effective immediately, to join Lumentum Holdings (LITE) as CEO. Ken Rizvi, the company's CFO, has been appointed interim CEO, and Nelson Chan, Chairman of the Board, will serve as Executive Chairman during the transition. The Board has initiated a search for a permanent CEO, considering both internal and external candidates. Concurrently, Synaptics released preliminary financial results for 2Q25, projecting revenue of approximately $267M, with gross margin in line with the midpoint of prior guidance, operating expenses slightly above the midpoint, and earnings per share exceeding the midpoint of the previous guidance.
  • Diageo (DEO) shares declined by 3% following its first-half results, where the company withdrew its medium-term guidance, citing ongoing macroeconomic and geopolitical uncertainties. While confident in long-term industry fundamentals and anticipating organic net sales growth in the second half of fiscal 2025, Diageo provided a more cautious outlook, including an expected pre-exceptional tax rate of around 24%, a stable effective interest rate of 4.3%, capital expenditures toward the upper end of the $1.3B–$1.5B range, and leverage exceeding its target range of 2.5–3.0x.

data.title: KKR raises bid for Fuji Soft, above Bain's offer - report
data.description:
Private equity firm KKR (NYSE:KKR) will raise its offer price for Japanese IT company Fuji Soft by more than 4% to take it above a rival offer from Bain Capital, Nikkei reported Tuesday.

KKR raised its price to 9,850 yen ($63.44) per share from 9,451 yen per share, compared to Bain's most recent offer of 9,600 yen ($61.82) per share, the report said.

KKR currently has a 33.97% stake in Fuji Soft following the first stage of a two-part bid in which two activist investors - 3D Investment Partners and Farallon Capital - agreed to tender their shares to KKR (NYSE:KKR).

KKR initially offered 8,800 yen a share for Fuji Soft last August.

data.title: TomTom N.V. GAAP EPS of -€0.05, revenue of €142.24M
data.description:
• TomTom N.V. press release (OTCPK:TMOAF): Q4 GAAP EPS of -€0.05.
  • Revenue of €142.24M (-0.8% Y/Y).
  • Location Technology revenue decreased by 2% to €122 million (Q4 '23: €125 million).
  • Automotive operational revenue increased by 6% to €88 million (Q4 '23: €83 million).
  • In Q4 '24, free cash flow was an outflow of €5 million versus an inflow of €5 million in the same quarter last year.
  • Net cash decreased, mainly due to a €39 million share buyback cash-out, to €264 million (FY '23: €315 million).
  • Automotive backlog decreased to €2.1 billion (FY '23: €2.5 billion).

data.title: European markets tick lower as tariff woes linger; Vodafone shares fall
data.description:
London (UKX) -0.38%

Germany (DAX:IND) -0.04%

France (CAC:IND) -0.09%

The pan-European Stoxx 600 (STOXX) slipped -0.53% on Tuesday amid concerns about the potential impacts of the tariffs announced by the Trump administration.

Trump has delays tariffs on Canada and Mexico by a month after last-minute talks with Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and Mexican President Claudia Sheinbaum, while China imposed tariffs and said that the countermoves will take effect on February 10.

Meanwhile, on the equities front, auto stocks moved lower, while telecommunication companies fell after Vodafone (VOD) reported another deterioration in Germany in its third quarter.

Coming up in the session: There are no major data releases.

In the bond market, the U.S. 10-year Treasury yield was up 3 basis points to 4.57%.

Germany's 10-year yield was up 2 basis points at 2.41%.

UK's 10-year yield was up 2 basis points to 4.52%.

data.title: Trump wants Ukraine's rare earth minerals in return for U.S. support
data.description:
President Donald Trump wants an agreement with Ukraine to access its rare earth minerals in return for the U.S. aiding the country's defense against Russia, saying he wants "equalization" from Kyiv for Washington's "close to $300B" in support.

"We're telling Ukraine they have very valuable rare earths," Trump told reporters at the White House on Monday. "We're looking to do a deal with Ukraine where they're going to secure what we're giving them with their rare earths and other things. We want a guarantee."

Rare earths refer to 17 elements used to make key components in cellphones, electric vehicles, wind turbines, and advanced weapons, among others. China currently dominates rare earth production and sales.

Trump indicated that the Ukraine government is willing to make a deal. "We're putting in hundreds of billions of dollars… I want security of the rare earth, and they're willing to do it."

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy in October unveiled his "victory plan" to strengthen Kyiv's defense against Russia, in which he offered western allies access to "natural resources and critical metals worth trillions of dollars," including uranium, titanium, lithium, graphite, and other resources.

The U.S. has been Kyiv's largest supporter since Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine in 2022. The U.S. Ukraine response funding totaled nearly $183B as of September 30, 2024, with $130.1B obligated and $86.7B disbursed, according to the federal Ukraine Interagency Oversight Working Group.
